Fix __host__/__device__ math-function ambiguities in catboost CUDA kernels.

CUDA 12.x's nvcc (with newer libcudacxx) restricts which standard-math
overloads are callable from __device__ code. Bare calls like

    pow(float, float)
    ceil(float)
    log(float)
    log2(float)
    sqrt(float)
    fabs(float) / abs(float-variable)
    std::exp(float)

resolve to the host-only overload set, producing diagnostics of the form:

    error: calling a __host__ function("X(float)") from a __device__ function

CUDA's runtime math header provides explicit *f-suffixed overloads
(powf, ceilf, logf, log2f, sqrtf, fabsf, expf) that ARE __device__-callable.
The fix is mechanical: replace the bare call with the *f-suffixed overload
when the argument(s) are float. We leave bare-double / bare-int calls alone
-- only the bare-float forms are broken.

Audited every catboost/cuda/**/*.{cu,cuh} call site exhaustively. All bare-
float calls (28 files, ~50 sites) are now patched. Coverage includes the
common idioms `(int)log2((float)gridDim.y)`, `if (abs(val) > 1e-20f)`, and
all CUDA-kernel pow/ceil/sqrt/fabs sites.

